he hospital as a space of institutional, medical, and ontological instability.In the hospital's clinics, biomedical practitioners struggle amid severe resource shortages to make the diseased body visible and knowable to the clinical gaze. That struggle is entangled with attempts by doctors, nurses, and patients to make themselves visible to external others-to kin, clinical experts, global scientists, politicians, and international development workers-as socially recognizable and valuable persons. Here hospital infrastructures emerge as relational technologies that are fundamentally fragile but also offer crucial opportunities for making people visible and knowable in new, unpredictable, and powerful ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aHospital patientszPapua New Guinea. 0aHospitalsxMedical staffzPapua New Guinea. 0aMedical carezPapua New Guinea. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822376668zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822376668423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822376668.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles